Basics of Analysis of Variance Test (ANOVA) and how to conduct it with R

This post elucidates main premises of ANOVA tests and shows how to conduct an ANOVA test using R with a real world data.
r
anova
data-analysis
Author

Muhammet Ozkaraca

Table of contents

  • Main Assumptions of ANOVA
  • Checking ANOVA assumptions

For this tutorial, I plan to revisit main concepts of the Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) test and implement it with R. ANOVA tests estimate how a quantitative dependent variable changes according to the levels of one or more categorical independent variables. In other words, using ANOVA, we can determine whether there is a statistically significant difference in the means of the groups with regards to the variable in question.

Note

As a rule of thumb, ANOVA tests are suitable for comparing three or more groups, while t-test is a better option when comparing two groups.

To conduct ANOVA test with a real-world example, I will use Olympic Medals dataset from TidyTuesday-Week 32 challenge. This dataset includes information on athletes participated in summer or winter games since Athens 1896 to Rio 2016. In this analysis, I will subset the whole dataset to the ones only received a gold medal in the games. So, the dependent variable will be the medal variable subsetted to the gold, retrieving the information only for athletes who won a gold medal in the games. For the independent variable, I will categorize athletes’ height into three different classes; short (<170 cm), medium (in between 170 cm and 185 cm), and tall (> 185 cm). Therefore, what will be inquired is to see whether there is a statistically significant difference across gold medal-winning athletes having different heights (Tall/Medium/Short).

Independent variables are the ones we, as researchers, would like to test whether they have an effect on the outcome such as the impact of poverty on school success.

Dependents variables are also called outcome variables. Taking the poverty and school success example, a student’s academic performance is a dependent variable and this can be influenced by a variety of factors such as his/her parents’ poverty, education, and etc.

Null and alternative hypotheses for this analysis are;
  • Null Hypothesis (\(H_{0}\)): Athletes, having Tall/Medium/Short height, are equal in terms of the number of gold medals they received.
    • \(\mu_{Tall Athletes}\) = \(\mu_{Medium Athletes}\) = \(\mu_{Short Athletes}\)
  • Alternative Hypothesis (\(H_{1}\)): At least one type of athletes is statistically different from others in terms of the number of gold medals they received.

  mutate(height_classification = case_when(height > 185 ~ "Tall Athlete",

Main Assumptions of ANOVA

ANOVA tests have four main assumptions that need to be examined. These assumptions, listed below along with their explanations, are crucial because if any of them are violated, the result of the ANOVA test cannot be considered statistically significant and therefore reliable.

Main Assumptions for ANOVA
Assumption Explanation
Variable Type For ANOVA tests, it is necessary to have a single continuous quantitative dependent variable (DV) and a qualitative independent variable (IV) with a minimum of two levels.
Independence ANOVA tests require that the observations within each group are independent of each other, and this condition can be verified based on the study design.
Normality ANOVA tests require the distribution of the residuals (the differences between the observed values and the predicted values) to be normal. In other words, the residuals should be normally distributed around zero. As a rule of thumb, for large sample sizes, normality is assumed to be satisfied. Note that, if normality is not met, the non-parametric test, Kruskal Wallis test, should be used instead of ANOVA.
Equality of Variances
(Homogeneity)		 In ANOVA tests, the variances of the groups should be equal. If Equality of Variances is not met, Welch ANOVA test should be used
Two ways to control normality assumption for the dependent variable
  1. Via visual depiction -> using Histogram and/or Quantile-Quantile Plot (QQ Plot)
  2. Via statistical testing -> using shapiro.test
    • the Null Hypothesis (\(H_{0}\)) is the data follows a normal distribution, while the alternative hypothesis (\(H_{1}\)) rejects that.
    • In this scenario, having \(p-value>0.05\) will demonstrate that there is not enough evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis (\(H_{0}\)) and therefore this criterion is met.
Two ways to control homogeneity assumption for the independent variable
  1. Via visual depiction -> using Histogram and/or Dot Plot and/or Scale-Location plot from plot() in R.
  2. Via statistical testing -> using Levene’s test and others such as Barlett’s test and etc.
    • the Null Hypothesis (\(H_{0}\)) is variances within groups are equal, while the alternative hypothesis (\(H_{1}\)) is variances within groups are not equal.
    • In this scenario, having \(p-value>0.05\) will demonstrate that there is not enough evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis (\(H_{0}\)) and therefore this criterion is met.

Checking ANOVA assumptions

After introducing the main premises of ANOVA test and the dataset, let’s go over whether the ANOVA test we will be pursuing satisfies the main assumptions.

Beginning with Variable Type, we will have a single continuous quantitative dependent variable (DV), which is the number of gold medals received by each category of athletes. In this case, category of athletes will be our qualitative independent variable (IV) with a minimum of two levels, . So, Variable Type assumption is satisfied ✅.

With regards to the Independence, the events in our dataset are independent from the each other as they are the result of each individual competation. So, Independence assumption is also satisfied ✅.

To check Normality assumption, there are two ways, either a visual inspection or a statistical test. Because the sample size for the dependent variable is higher than 5000 and therefore it is above the limit for the shapiro test, I will choose to stick with the visual inspection. The below figure demonstrates the distribution for the dependent variable.

    As seen from the figure, the dependent variable follows a slightly normal distribution, in addition to the fact that we have a large sample size in here, we can accept the null hypothesis that he data follows a normal distribution and normality assumption is met ✅.

    With a p-value below 0.05 as a result of the Shapiro test, we can reject the null hypothesis that the data follows a normal distribution. However, considering the sample size in our case, we can assume that the normality assumption is met ✅.

    As a last step, to check Homogeneity assumption, we again have two options: either a visual inspection or a statistical test. The below panel tab demonstrates the result for both.

    Beginning with the histogram, it is evident that the variances within each group are high due to the right-skewed distribution of the number of terror events. Upon examining the dot plot, it becomes apparent that the variances within each group also exhibit a considerable variation. To statistically test this using Levene’s test in the third panel, the resulting p−value is found to be lower than 0.05, indicating sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis that the variances are equal across groups.
